Data Preprocessing

Data Selection: Description of the Dataset and Selecting the Dataset

The dataset for this project is called "Cervical Cancer (Risk Factors)" which focuses on the prediction of indicators/diagnosis of cervical cancer. There are 36 features within the dataset which covers over demographic information, patients' habits, and historic medical records of 858 patients. It was collected at the 'Hospital Universitario de Caracas' in Caracas, Venezuela. Due to privacy concerns, some information is missing as patients were not obligated to share everything about their health.

The dataset was found on UCI Machine Learning Repository and was published by authors Kelwin Fernandes, Jaime Cardoso, and Jessica Fernandes. Link to dataset: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/383/cervical+cancer+risk+factors

Cervical cancer is a type of cancer that starts in the cervix and usually spreads to other body parts in its later critical stages. It is the fourth most common cancer found amongst women. The occurence of this disease illustrates the importance of understanding the different indicators that may lead to increased chances of cervical cancer in patients. Using a feedforward neural network (FNN) and having cervical cancer as the target (Dx: Cancer), FNN can be used for cancer classification due to its nature of learning complex patterns through hidden layer architecture.

Cervical Cancer Risk Factors Dataset Variables Description

Variable Name Description
Age The age of the patient.
Number of sexual partners Number of sexual partners the patient has had.
First sexual intercourse Age at which the patient had their first sexual intercourse.
Num of pregnancies The number of pregnancies the patient has had.
Smokes Whether the patient is a smoker (1 = smoker, 0 = non-smoker).
Smokes (years) The number of years the patient has been smoking.
Smokes (packs/year) The number of packs of cigarettes the patient smokes per year.
Hormonal Contraceptives Whether the patient has used hormonal contraceptives (1 = yes, 0 = no).
Hormonal Contraceptives (years) The number of years the patient has used hormonal contraceptives.
IUD Whether the patient has used an intrauterine device (IUD) (1 = yes, 0 = no).
IUD (years) The number of years the patient has used an intrauterine device (IUD).
STDs Whether the patient has had any sexually transmitted diseases (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs (number) The number of sexually transmitted diseases the patient has had.
STDs:condylomatosis Whether the patient has had condylomatosis, a type of genital wart (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs:cervical condylomatosis Whether the patient has had cervical condylomatosis, a type of genital wart (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs:vaginal condylomatosis Whether the patient has had vaginal condylomatosis, a type of genital wart (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs:vulvo-perineal condylomatosis Whether the patient has had vulvo-perineal condylomatosis, a type of genital wart (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs:syphilis Whether the patient has had syphilis (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs:pelvic inflammatory disease Whether the patient has had pelvic inflammatory disease (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs:genital herpes Whether the patient has had genital herpes (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs:molluscum contagiosum Whether the patient has had molluscum contagiosum (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs:HPV Whether the patient has had human papillomavirus (HPV) (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs:HIV Whether the patient has had HIV (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs:hepatitis B Whether the patient has had hepatitis B (1 = yes, 0 = no).
STDs: Number of Diagnosis The number of times the patient has had some form of STD (continuous)
STDs:Time since first diagnosis The time that has passed since they first got some form of STD
STDs:Time since last diagnosis The time that has passed since they last got some form of STD
Dx: Cancer Whether the patient has had cervical cancer (1 = yes, 0 = no).
Dx: CIN Whether patient has had cervical intraepithelial neoplasia which is a precancerous condition that describes abnormal cells in the cervix (1 = yes, 0 = no)
Dx:HPV Whether that patient has had human papillomavirus (HPV) (1 = yes, 0 = no).
Dx: Whether that patient has had some general diagnosis, could be diagnosis of cervical issue (1 = positive diagnosis, 0 = no diagnosis).
Hinselmann: Results from the Hinselmann test, which is a dignostic test used to detect abnormal cells in the cervix. Used to identify precancerous leisons. (1 = abnormal result, 0 = normal results).
Schiller: Results from the Schiller test, a diagnostic test where iodine is applied to the cervix to detect abnormal cells that might indicate precancerous changes (1 = abnormal result, 0 = normal results).
Cytology: Results from the pap smear test which examines cervical cells for abnormalities. (1 = abnormal result, 0 = normal results).
Biopsy: Whether a biopsy was performed and if it was positive for precancerous leisons. (1 = positive result, 0 = negative result).

Data Cleaning

Handling Missing Values

Missing values in this dataset appears in the form of question marks. Therefore, using .isnull() which is an attribute of the pandas dataframe is not possible. Therefore, there is a need to turn all the question marks values into null values and then count the number of missing values from each column. If the percentage of missing is greater than 30%, that data type will be dropped entirely as it suggests that a large proportion of that dataset is unavailable. However, if the percentage of missing is under 30%, I will need to impute missing values.

  1. Case 1: If the variable is categorical, then the variable is imputed using mode imputation
  2. Case 2: If the variable is numerical, then the variable is imputed using median imputation

This shows that variables Num of pregnancies, Number of sexual partners, First sexual intercourse, IUD years, Smoke (years), Hormonal Contraceptives (years), Smokes (packs/year) and STDs:(number) cannot be categorical values due to the number of unique values they have which suggests that they are nominal data with no ordered ranking. This means that their imputation method will be through median imputation.

Regarding the categorical variables STDs:AIDS and STDs: cervical condylomatosis, they only have one unique value. This means that mode imputation will yield only one value for their respective columns. Since this categorical variable only has one class level, it means that there is no variability and so the information that this feature contributes to the model will be very redundant. It is best to drop these two features entirely as they will not enhance the predictive performance of our neural network model.

Summary of Data Preprocessing Steps

In the preprocessing process, the features used to train the model excluding the target was 35. Two of the features Time since First Diagnosis and Time since last diagnosis had missing values percentage that was greater than 92% which means imputing it would mean that too much synthetic data would have to be made. Hence, they were dropped from the dataset entirely.

From there, two more variables were dropped because they only had one class-level. These two variables were STDs:AIDS and STDs: cervical condylomatosis which suggests that they were likely redundant information that would not add any predictive performance to the model. Hence, the dataset was reduced from the shape of (858, 35) to (858, 31) excluding the target from the feature column.

From their, the numerical variables that had missing values were imputed using median imputation. These variables were Num of pregnancies, Number of sexual partners, First sexual intercourse, IUD years, Smoke (years), Hormonal Contraceptives (years), Smokes (packs/year) and STDs:(number). The categorical variables with missing values were imputed using mode imputation. Those variables were STDs:HIV, STDs:HPV, Smokes, STDs:molluscum contagiosum, STDs:genital herpes, Hormonal Contraceptives, STDs:pelvic inflammatory disease, IUD, STDs:syphilis, STDs, STDs:Hepatitis B, STDs:condylomatosis, STDs:vaginal condylomatosis and STDs:vulvo-perineal condylomatosis.

Once these preprocessing steps were completed, the next step is to move onto the data splitting process.

  1. This imbalanced means that the model may place weight on variables by assuming that they are important towards the overall predictive performance.
  2. The model will become very biased in predicting for the majority class.
  3. This also means that the model will have a difficult time generalizing for the minority class which makes it difficult to classify them due to difficulty in uncovering the patterns.

Handling Data Imbalances

SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) was used due to the fact that the minority class (Dx:Cancer = 0) has very little instances in the whole dataset. Since the majority class is highly over-represented, there will be biasedness towards that class because there are more examples from that class and so there will be higher accuracy for predicting the majority class but will perform terribly on the minority class.

The aim of SMOTE is to generate synthetic data points for the minority class.

Introducing Class Weights for Heavily Imbalanced Dataset

The idea of class weights is to place emphasis on the minority class in the model which is heavily underepresented in this dataset. This allows the majority class to not dominate the learning process. Class weights are useful to avoid the model learning to predict only the majority class for every input because in real-life this is not useful. In the real-world, a model is more useful when its able to identify the 5% chance that someone has cancer compared to identifying 95% that they do not. A misclassification is really consequential for medical diagnosis as it affects life and death.

The logic behind class weights is to multiply the loss by a weight associated with that class. The higher the weight for that class, the more the model will focus on minimizing classification errors for that class. This helps the model pay more attention and improve its ability to correctly predict the minority class.

In[1530]:
import numpy as np

# Convert the result into a dictionary
class_weight_dict = {classes[i]: class_weights[i] for i in range(len(classes))}

Since my data is highly imbalanced, using the accuracy metric is not an accurate representation of how good the model is. This is because high accuracy reflects the model's biasedness towards the majority class. Therefore, the accuracy does not reflect how well the model is performing on the minority class. Hence, other metrics such as the confusion matrix and the AUC-ROC curve will be used as indicators of model performance. To prioritize this, the metric parameter will take in the AUC function from the keras.metrics package.

Rationalization of parameter choices for neural network

Input Dimension: 31: This is the input dimension of the neural network which represents the number of features in the dataset excluding the target variable. 31 was the number of features remaining after some features were dropped due to proportion of missingness and some features were also dropped because they only had one class level which implies that they are likely redundant features that does not contribute to the model at all.

Hidden Layer: 1: The choice to use only one hidden layer is because it is usually sufficient to for any continuous function to be approximated given that there are enough hidden neurons in the hidden layer. With one hidden layer, it is less prone to overfitting because there are fewer parameters that are needed to be optimized which means it works really well with smaller datasets. Given that this dataset only has 858 instances and the training samples have 504 samples after SMOTE, one hidden layer should be sufficient and should be the most ideal.

Number of Nodes in Hidden Layer: 16 16 neurons was used purely as a starting point because neural networks generalize better when the neurons count is small. Higher neurons in the hidden layer leads to overfitting because the model will memorize the training data. Small starting point for neurons will be able to capture the essential patterns of the dataset much better.

Activation Function (Hidden Layer): Rectified Linear Unit (ReLu): This activation function is known for introducing non-linearity to a neural network model which allows the model to learn complex patterns that are not always linear-based. Moreover, ReLU does not suffer from the vanishing gradient problem like other activation functions (namely Tanh or Sigmoid). This is because ReLU outputs a gradient of 1 for any positive input and 0 for any negative input. It has a faster convergence nature which leads to quicker training and is computationally inexpensive.

$$ \phi(x) = max(0, \alpha(x)) \phi'(\alpha(x)) = \begin{cases} 1 & \text{if} \alpha(x) > 0 \\ 0 & \text{if} \alpha(x) \leq 0 \\ \end{cases} $$

Activation Function (Output Layer): Sigmoid: The classification for this neural network is to determined whether or not a person has cervical cancer which is a binary classification and therefore needs the sigmoid activation function. Useful for outputting probabilities as it maps any input as 0 or 1. The sigmoid function is denoted as follows:

$$ \sigma(x) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-x}} $$

Optimizer: Adam The Adaptive Moment Estimation optimizer adjusts the learning rate for each parameter based on the parameter's gradient first and second moments. The learning rate is therefore adjusted depending on the weight of each parameter so its useful for features that have varying magnitudes.

Loss: Binary Cross-entropy Binary Cross-entropy is used for binary classification problems where the output layer uses the sigmoid activation function. It is useful to train classifiers to output probabilities and learn from mistakes when the model is confident but is wrong when classifying labels.

Class Weight: {0: 0.509, 1: 25.7} based on the computed class weight determined by the frequency of each class in the dataset.

Hyperparameter Tuning

Our hyperparameter tuning process will attempt to find the best combinations for the following parameters:

  1. Learning_rates
  2. Dropout_rates
  3. Num_nodes_options
  4. Batch_size
  5. Number of Epochs

Creating a generalized function to test the randomized search algorithm

In[1548]:
import random
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense, Dropout
from keras.optimizers import Adam
from keras.metrics import AUC

# Function to create a model with random hyperparameters
def create_model(learning_rate=0.001, dropout_rate=0.2, num_nodes=64):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(num_nodes, input_dim=X_train_res.shape[1], activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(dropout_rate))
    model.add(Dense(num_nodes, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(dropout_rate))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate), loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=[AUC()])
    return model

# Setting up the parameter grid
learning_rates = [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1]
dropout_rates = [0.0, 0.2, 0.3, 0.4, 0.5]
num_nodes_options = [32, 64, 128, 256]
batch_sizes = [16, 32, 64, 128]
epochs_options = [50, 100, 200]

# Randomly sampling hyperparameters
num_samples = 5  # Number of samples to test
best_auc = 0
best_model = None
best_params = {}

# List to store the history of the top 3 models based on AUC
best_models_history = []
best_auc_values = []

for i in range(num_samples):
    # Randomly select hyperparameters
    learning_rate = random.choice(learning_rates)
    dropout_rate = random.choice(dropout_rates)
    num_nodes = random.choice(num_nodes_options)
    batch_size = random.choice(batch_sizes)
    epochs = random.choice(epochs_options)
    
    # Build the model with sampled hyperparameters
    model_new = create_model(learning_rate=learning_rate, dropout_rate=dropout_rate, num_nodes=num_nodes)
    
    # Train the model with class weights
    history = model_new.fit(X_train_res, y_train_res, batch_size=batch_size, epochs=epochs, verbose=0, 
                            class_weight=class_weight, validation_data=(X_test, y_test))
    
    # Print available keys in the history dictionary to debug the issue
    print(f"Model {i+1} - History keys: {history.history.keys()}")
    
    #Calculating AUC manually 
    y_pred_proba = model_new.predict(X_test)  # Probability predictions (not hard labels)
    auc_score = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba)  # Compute AUC using sklearn's roc_auc_score
    
    #Track the best model and history based on AUC
    if auc_score > best_auc:
        best_auc = auc_score
        best_model = model_new
        best_params = {
            'learning_rate': learning_rate,
            'dropout_rate': dropout_rate,
            'num_nodes': num_nodes,
            'batch_size': batch_size,
            'epochs': epochs
        }
        best_models_history = [history]  # Reset with the current best model history
        best_auc_values = [auc_score]
        
    elif len(best_models_history) < 3:
        best_models_history.append(history)  # Store additional top-performing models' history
        
        best_auc_values.append(auc_score)
    elif auc_score > min(best_auc_values):
        #Replace the model with the smallest AUC
        worst_index = best_auc_values.index(min(best_auc_values))
        best_models_history[worst_index] = history
        best_auc_values[worst_index] = auc_score

# Plotting the learning curves for the best three models individually
for i, history in enumerate(best_models_history):
    
    # Plotting the training & validation loss for each model
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label=f'Model {i+1} Train Loss')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label=f'Model {i+1} Val Loss')
    plt.title(f'Model {i+1} - Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

print(f"Best Parameters: {best_params}")
print(f"Best AUC: {best_auc:.4f}")

Model Interpretation

The model is limited by the fact that even with using SMOTE to oversample the minority class and using class weights to add penalty for wrongful classifications, there needs to be more training data with more observations with the minority class in order for the model to learn more complicated patterns that can correctly classify cancer outcomes. Having more observation with actual data from the hospital will make training model much more better.

The variables that likely influenced the results of the model is the right-skewed variables in this dataset. Especially, the right-skewed categorical variables and the right-skewed numerical variables. Despite, the right skewed-numerical variables being transformed using log transformation, the shape of their distribution did not change much. Therefore, these variables were more biased towards the majority class.

Conclusion

Recap of entire process: In the preprocessing process, the features used to train the model excluding the target was 35. Two of the features Time since First Diagnosis and Time since last diagnosis had missing values percentage that was greater than 92% which means imputing it would mean that too much synthetic data would have to be made. Hence, they were dropped from the dataset entirely. From there, two more variables were dropped because they only had one class-level. These two variables were STDs:AIDS and STDs: cervical condylomatosis which suggests that they were likely redundant information that would not add any predictive performance to the model. Hence, the dataset was reduced from the shape of (858, 35) to (858, 31) excluding the target from the feature column.

From their data was split into training/testing/split using 70-15-15 configuration and was stratified based on the proportions of the original dataset. Due to the imbalanced nature of the dataset, the training set was resampled using SMOTE. Originally, the training set had the shape of (257, 31) but the SMOTED training set had (504, 31). The goal was to oversample the minority class so that the model would not just predict the majority class all the time. Moreover, the distribution of the variables were checked to see how they could influence the model during the training. The numerical variables with right-skewed distribution were transformed using log-transformed. The categorical variables that were right-skewed were kept as they are because encoding binary variables would not change their feature behavior during training.

From there to make sure that the model prioritized classifying the minority class as well, class weights were used to add penalty for wrongful misclassifications. These class weights were computed using the ratio of the majority class and minority class in the original dataset. From there, the initial model architecture was made by the following parameter choices:

  1. Hidden Layer: 1, 16 neurons
  2. Activation Function for Hidden Layer: ReLu
  3. Activation Function for Output Layer: Sigmoid
  4. Optimizer: Adam
  5. Loss: Binary Cross-entropy
  6. Metric: AUC
  7. Learning Rate: 0.001
  8. Epochs: 50
  9. Batch Size: 0
  10. Dropout Rate: 0

The choice to use the AUC Metric is because accuracy is not a good metric for an imbalanced data since the model will keep on classifying the majority class. Hence, looking at AUC and the confusion matrix would show how well the model is at classifying.

Through Hyperparamater tuning, the best parameters for the model with the highest AUC was the following configuration:

  1. Hidden Layer: 1, 32 neurons
  2. Activation Function for Hidden Layer: ReLu
  3. Activation Function for Output Layer: Sigmoid
  4. Optimizer: Adam
  5. Loss: Binary Cross-entropy
  6. Metric: AUC
  7. Learning Rate: 0.001
  8. Epochs: 50
  9. Batch Size: 16
  10. Dropout Rate: 0.2

There were improvement following the hyperparameter tuning process. Namely, the AUC metric increased and the confusion matrix also improved with less wrongful classifications than the initial model. Here, are the differences between the two:

Initial Model Test AUC: 0.5361 Best Model Test AUC: 0.5695

The final model classifies the non-cancer cases much more effectively than the initial model. However, the initial model was able to classifying some cancerous cases correctly but had several wrongful classifications.

For instance, the initial model classified those with not cancer in the cancer category which showcases high Type I Error. It had less wrongful classification for those that have cancer but predicted them as no (5 total) which means the initial model had less cases of Type II Error. The final model had only 7 misclassifications for those with cancer but predicted as no. The issue with this is that Type II error in medical diagnosis is costly as it can affect a person's life. By having wrongful misclassifications, it showcases the limitations of this dataset and the model.

Overall, while the AUC improved for the final model, we can see that the confusion matrix showcases the limitation of this particular dataset as there were simply not enough instances of good data for the minority class. This skewed the prediction drastically towards the majority class which means the model is really good at handling majority class classification. However, even with hyperparameter tuning, the model would still only classify the majority class well and struggle with the minority class. If possible, when the hospital is able to collect more data, the model may be better at classifying.
